segments.text: We're not worried about that.
Just trying to find out a little bit.
Listen, Jackson, you mentioned earlier that your son went to Allen Academy.
And then went to A&M.
And then went to A&M.
Could you tell us something about the education system?
Has it changed very much from the time that your son went to school to now?
Odella, I'm not sure I could help you at that point.
Because I just...
When he went to Allen Academy, see, that was the military too.
And that helped him a lot to go to A&M.
In fact, he was next to the best freshman, real freshman on the campus.
And it just made him sick that he walked through the vest, stood up all afternoon.
But he said, brother, my thumb just got so it wouldn't work.
He stood up.
But he was strictly military.
But I don't know how that thing's run now.
See, I can't make that comparison because I just don't have any connection with it now.
I have access to it, but it really just doesn't go places by itself.
I could go to anything on the campus, but as far as having access to it.
But I don't go because you just don't go alone.
And I can't make that comparison.
I just don't know how.
I don't think they're near as strict as they used to be.
Well, what was the reason for Allen Academy to be out there in the first place?
Do you have any idea?
Well, they were for younger boys, boys from wealthy homes and broken homes and things like that.
The parents just felt like they wanted them in a private school.
A lot of them were able to send them.
Others, you hate to say it, but they were from broken homes.
We sent Clarkie there because Mr. Allen was a Methodist, and he, well, he just did a lot for the Methodist boys, just out of the goodness of his heart.
We never could have sent him there because it was an exclusive school and a very good school, a very good school.
And a lot of the parents sent them there because it was kind of a preparatory school for, you know, from high school.
to college is a pretty big jump, you see.
And that was a junior college.
It was a step between high school, and then Allen Academy, and then college.
It's an awful big jump from high school to college.
I don't know how a lot of them ever make it.
I'm a firm believer in a junior college.
And that's what it was.
And they weren't there.
Because so many of these little old freshmen come here that right out of high school, they just can't make it.
It's too big a jump.
And as I say, a lot of people sent them for that preparatory work for college, and others sent them because they were from broken homes, and they didn't mortgage a small amount.
They had to send them somewhere, those that were left with their mothers.
You see, their mothers had to get work or something like that.
It's the only child you give your mother.
But it was a very good school.
Do you think maybe some of the inflow that came in had something to do with Allen Academy?
People coming in from, say, the surrounding towns?
Yes, I think it did.
I think it did.
Not as much so as the other class, I don't believe.
Because I'll tell you why.
The high schools here were good.
The people that came here to make their homes here, you see, sent them to high school.
to the high schools in Bryan.
Then you have one out here.
That's why I said, look, Clarkie took two years at the high school in Bryan before he went to Allen County.
He did go to the high school in Bryan two years, and then he wanted to go to Allen County, and Mr. Allen wanted him there.
He had a very fine school soul.
That's when he switched.
And then that kind of got him ready for A&M.
But I think the Bryan High School has always been a good high school.
And I think the people that live in Bryan, I don't think they felt the necessity of it, you see, because they had a good school there.
They had excellent teachers.
It's always been a good high school.
Now I think A&M kind of.
Matches wits with them.
But we didn't even have a high school.
And now don't they have three or four at A&M?
Several, I understand.
I don't know how many elementary schools they have.
But the kids on the campus didn't even have a place to go.
Those professors' children, they met in a little frame building over there.
And I think they did have good teachers, but they didn't have anything to work with.
The teachers were the professors' wives, you see.
And most of those professors married old maid school teachers.
And they were smart, but they didn't know anything about kids.
You know, it takes an old maid to tell you how to raise kids.
You only have the one child in the house?
That's the one.
But Bob, he makes up for a dozen.
Does he live here in Bryan?
No, he doesn't.
He lives in Houston.
He lives in Houston.
But he was an Aggie from here to there.
And I am, too.
There's not much of me, but it's all Aggies.
But did the college draw in on a lot of these small outside, you know, like what is this out here?
Steep Hollow?
Yes, quite a few.
But I have to say, I believe Blinn College at Brenham.
gets more of that class than we do on county expenses.
Glenn is so much cheaper than A&M.
Much cheaper than A&M, and a lot of them drive and go.
They just commute and go.
And it was cheaper than paying dormitory fees and things like that.
No, not as many, I don't think, as should, as they should.
But I think that's the reason.
I think that's the reason.
Now, they seem like they got more from Caldwell than anywhere.
A lot of people from Caldwell.
See, it's close.
They can commute there, too.
But these other outlying posts, it was just about tit for tat, and they took the cheapest one.
And then Glenn offers a night course, and they could...
They could do that too, though they couldn't go in daytime, they could take a night course or two, and they got started that way.
Since you as a preacher's wife, I imagine y'all came across or seen some of the sore spots or the, you know, not so happy spots, you might say, I'd say Brian, as it was growing, it's
Yes, we saw them more than once.
And yet, I don't believe there's ever been the trouble here that a lot of other places have had.
They seem to have...
Each class, they just seemed to have accepted everybody.
I think one reason for that, and I hate to say it, is that they didn't mix and mingle.
Each class just kind of stayed to themselves, and they didn't cause anybody in trouble.
And that's unfortunate.
They should have been drawn together.
And the boys on the campus, that worried us a lot.
these foreign boys that came to A&M, and now the Negroes, you know, we have quite a few of them now, but you never see them with anybody else.
They just go with themselves, only in the field of athletics.
They seem to be on equal ground in athletics, but haven't you noticed it on the campus?
They just go in cliques with themselves.
I don't know what would happen if they mingled and fraternized with each other.
I don't know what the score would be there, because they don't do it.
And we had three or four of those neighbors to join our church.
They'd come, and if there's a seat by themselves anywhere in that house, they'd get over there in that corner by themselves.
And the first thing we knew, they just quit coming.
Why?
We don't know, because everybody was cartridge-filling.
I think that people went out of their way to make them feel
welcome.
But they didn't feel.
And then our West Foundation has a very good recreation program there.
Very good.
And they insist on the students.
It's open to everybody.
But the Negroes never come.
The Negroes never come.
And it's unfortunate.
Because it's there for them.
But they don't come.
Why is that?
But I think that I don't know what would happen if they all got together
Maybe it would be friction.
And yet they get along so well in their athletics, you know.
And they make no discrimination at all, the coaches or the boys either, I don't think.
You may know more about that than I do, but with my observation, I don't think they discriminate at all.
